# Tests (operator-specific, not for public OSS tree)
#
# Deny-by-default: test files can carry grid names, meter numbers and org IDs,
# and they also arrive here from upstream syncs, so nothing under a tests/
# directory is published until it has been checked. Vetted files are tracked
# individually with `git add -f` — around 100 are, which is why the suites in
# chat_orchestrator/, shared/, mcp_servers/ and anansi_app/ run in CI.
#
# Because gitignore does not apply to already-tracked files, those stay tracked
# normally; only *new* test files need the -f. A plain `git add` on one is a
# no-op and the commit will silently omit it. See "Adding a new test file" in
# CONTRIBUTING.md before broadening this pattern.
#
# The entry below names a file that exists upstream but must not be published.
# Git does not need it — the blanket tests/ rule already hides it — but
# .github/scripts/check_test_wiring.py reads these explicit .py entries as the
# list of tests that are unpublished *on purpose*. Anything else it finds
# untracked under a tests/ directory fails the commit as a probable silent drop.
# So: to withhold a test file, name it here.
tests/
mcp_servers/tests/test_meter_actions.py

# Scripts — only .gs and .js files are public; all .py/.sh are internal
# Exception: backfill_design_artifacts.py is generic gd_designs.artifacts backfill
# logic (no org IDs/secrets/site names), tracked with git add -f
scripts/*.py
scripts/*.sh
scripts/*.png

